I've never met anyone who understood crypto and couldn't program at all, but I guess in theory I want the latter too.
I'm not a particularly good or experienced recruiter, so I'm sure others are having more success than me!
Currently, all I care is that they understand "high-level" crypto.
In part selection bias, as I don't get many good candidates to interview - they'd already be working/consulting. :(
Equally, if you can't understand pointers, you may still be able to do good work at lower-level as a HW designer!
*That* failure has nothing to do with a lack of math; everything to do with a lack of high-level understanding.
It's the crypto equivalent to comp-sci students not understanding pointers basically.
...they don't understand how a key can sign a message *giving meaning* to another key - they don't get delegation.
Where people fail is that while they know the "textbook RSA" explanations...
Also, because people are unfamiliar with the RFC, I heavily prompt them/let them design their own PGP protocol.
I've never actually had an interview where the candidate understood web-of-trust.
e.g. I like to use "explain how OpenPGP works" as an interview Q, and find ppl w/ math-level crypto that can't do it.
And often, people who understand the math deeply design terrible high-level systems using that math.
In my experience, often have to compromise: doesn't exist enough people who understand both low-level and high-level.
The crypto primitives are sufficiently "black boxed" now that the failures happen on layers above them.
Blockchain stuff _is_ weird, as you can definitely do good work w/o understanding insides of the crypto "black boxes"
But then again, I also like cave exploration, an activity that w/o good safety practices is downright deadly.
Prior to this line of work I did analog electronics design; I actually enjoyed high-stakes/safety-relevant work.
Yup, and incompetence is often task specific; I've often said "X will never understand security, but they do great Y"
It's also an industry plagued by scams - I've often done due dilligence on ppl who turned out to be actual scammers.

That's why I said "more likely" - due to circumstances in BTC/blockchain, it's a lot more likely.
...and also, there's a distinction between unskilled and incompetent too - former has the potential to learn.
If a competent person makes a mistake, further investment may still be valuable; w/ incompetent they're not changing.
For that specific issue, I think it's very important to be able to say people are incompetent if they are.
...they have reached out and asked me for advice on how to improve their security. Happens surprisingly often!

15. It was news that, if not described very precisely and carefully, could be easily misconstrued, no question.
14. We can debate whether it should be leaked, and how likely it is to be become policy. But what AP reported was not "fake news".
13. If there is an intention to use National Guard as an immigration police force, it's a proposal that should be very critically debated.
12. Most soldiers have no appropriate training in law enforcement. This is a popular misconception that causes much mischief/harm.
11. Ironically, it says National Guard personnel are uniquely trained and qualified to serve this role, which is untrue.
10. But it does clearly envision using National Guard personnel to investigate, apprehend, and detain illegal immigrants.
9. No, it doesn't formally "mobilize" (take federal command of) National Guard units. Nor does it mention "deportation".
8. As I read it, the memo clearly proposes mandating National Guard soldiers (under state command) to enforce immigration laws.
7. On the substance: a lot of the "debunking" of the memo's substantive proposals seem like nitpicking to me.
6. A more appropriate response would be to put the memo in context and deny that it is policy, not that it exists.
5. That said, if the memo is authentic, the White House's blanket denials (100% untrue) of the AP story are unwarranted, and inaccurate.
4. When unrefined policy ideas or memos get leaked to the public, it could alert, but it could also confuse.
3. Second, it IS problematic when proposals that aren't policy get leaked. There's a place for considering ideas that later get rejected.
